<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-037-213 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 453 806</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Oct 9 1991 n169 p15(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications (UK)1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM targets Ami Pro as Signature falters. (may launch wordprocessing software after cancelling launch of its own Signaturepackage)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woolacott, Emma.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Licenses)Lotus Development Corp. (Licenses).andO;Ticker:    IBM; LOTS.andO;Product:   Freelance (Presentation software) (Licenses)Ami Professional 2.0 (Word processing software) (Licenses)Signature (Word processing software) (Product development).andO;Topic:     LicensingNegotiationPresentation softwareWord processing software.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM is considering licensing Lotus' Ami Pro word processor and Feelancegraphics package, following the last-minute cancellation of the launch of itsSignature word processing software.andM;Signature was developed by IBM's Desktop Software Division (IDS) incollaboration with XyQuest, and was intended as a successor to IBM'sDisplayWrite.andP;  An IBM spokeswoman confirmed that Signature is on hold, andadded that the future of IDS itself is under review.andM;Sources close to Jim Manzi, Lotus' president and CEO, told PC User that hehas been discussing a licensing deal for Ami Pro 2.0 and Freelance withcolleagues since March this year.andP;  Freelance would be a replacement for theHollywood presentation graphics package, another IDS product.andP;  IDS was neveras successful as chairman John Akers hoped when he founded it three yearsago.andP;  Analysts agree that a deal with Lotus could be in the offing.andM;DisplayWrite, despite being IDS' most successful product, never succeeded incapturing more than around 6.5 per cent of the UK word processing market.andO;One UK analyst said:  &quot;We heard a rumor that IBM was talking to Lotus.andP;  Itseems that they talked about Ami Pro -- and then IBM delayed its product.&quot;andM;Lotus officials would not confirm the rumours.andP;  But Mark Mallinson, productmarketing manager for Ami Pro, commented:  &quot;We are in the process ofdeveloping an OS/2 version, and IBM is happy for us to do that.&quot;andP;  He added: &quot;The way Ami Pro has been developed means it is a relatively easy task todevelop a full OS/2 Presentation Manager version.&quot;andM;Steve Jack, product marketing manager for Freelance, said:  &quot;If it's lookingto pick up Freelance, we'd be delighted.&quot;andM;Jeff Ramsay, a marketing representative with XyQuest, promised that Signaturewould eventually be released.andP;  But he said IBM and XyQuest had not yet agreedon how and when the product would be marketed -- and by whom.andP;  &quot;I'm tellingcustomers to check in two weeks,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>